@realmoney Apr 20, 2020 | 05:04 PM EDT DOUG KASS Oil Vey: A Demand and Supply Shock * The largest drop ever in energy consumption combined with a supply glut led to the historic plunge in oil prices The drop in the price of oil was the most newsworthy item of the day. I am

not an oil futures trader, so this isn't really my wheelhouse -- but here are my explanations of today's bizarre collapse in the price of oil (May futures contract): * The sharp decline in the price of oil is a function of the unprecedented demand shock coupled with the recent

supply additions. * On the demand side, there are several market-stressing events. The global economy turned off ... and so did energy usage. Few are leaving their houses (so much of the world's population isn't driving much, if at all). There is also a massive drop in airline

traffic and a dramatic reduction in industrial demand. * On the supply side, the dispute between Saudi Arabia and Russia -- aimed at destroying the U.S. shale business (and apparently succeeding) -- contributed to a robust increase in supply and accelerated the energy

demand/supply imbalance. * In all likelihood the negative print (of -$37/barrel) on the May futures is likely a function of market structure distortions from the machines coupled with the proliferation of energy-related exchange-traded funds like USO (USO) (which owns 25%-30% of

total open interest of most maturities) as well as the leveraged oil ETFs. * Since non-commercials were net short, non-hedge fund traders weren't likely market disruptive. But some hedge funds could have had some problems. Remember Amaranth Advisors' loss of $6 billion in

natural gas futures back in 2006 - and how it destabilized that market? I have been negative for oil stocks for years, but it is now time to revisit that negativity based on the cannon-like price destabilization that occurred today and the improving reward vs. risk in energy
stocks. More tomorrow on this. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @lizclaman @business @realdonaldtrump @riskreversal @terranovajoe @guyadami

@realdonaldtrump Many, including myself, are concerned about the implications of Trump’s tweets and the actions of protestors in a smattering of locations across the nation It is undeniable that no president has ever made a more dangerous statement than Trump’s “LIBERATE” tweets

But we should keep the events in perspective. In urging perspective, I am not dismissing the gravity of Trump’s reckless actions. The first step in maintaining perspective is to acknowledge the unavoidable amplification generated by media coverage. While Trump sent a clarion call

to his supporters, only a few hundred showed up around the nation. On a percentage basis, their numbers are effectively equal to zero. The ugly images beamed into our homes trick us into over-weighting the prevalence of the phenomenon—the so-called “availability bias”

identified by Nobel Prize winner Daniel Kahneman. The “availability bias” is a mental shortcut that helps us interpret the prevalence and significance of events. In many situations, the bias works well, but in a world where cable news is dependent on dramatic video, it causes us

to misinterpret the true magnitude of events. Let’s do the math to see what the small protests in Michigan tell us. Michigan has a population of ten million people. At most, a couple of hundred protestors showed up at the state capitol. What you did not see on your television

was 9,999,800 citizens of Michigan peacefully remaining at home—as Governor Witmer requested. A rational comparison based on the numbers tells us that the protests were insignificant—despite breathless commentators and frightening pictures. To be fair, there are undoubtedly many

people in Michigan who sympathize with the protestors. Okay, let’s look at that. As noted above in a Politico article, most Americans are much more worried about easing restrictions too early than they are about the effect on the economy. Per the poll, about 47% of Republicans

in Michigan are more concerned about the economy than the pandemic. Per a recent PEW Research study, only 34% of Michigan voters are Republican. Even if all 47% of Republicans in Michigan who are worried about the economy want to “liberate” their state—a doubtful proposition—

that would mean that only 16% of Michigan voters support Trump’s call to resist social distancing measures (0.47 X 0.34 = 0.16). Apologies for the math, but it is important that we place Trump’s threats in perspective. For comparison, 29% of Americans believe in Bigfoot, so if

only 16% of voters in Michigan are motivated by Trump’s tweets to “liberate” Michigan, they represent the unavoidable tail in any distribution curve that represents the outliers. In trying to put Trump’s irresponsible tweets in perspective, I do not mean to minimize the very

real economic duress and social discontent that are broadly felt by Americans of every political party. But no one should fear that such discontent can be converted into armed resistance by Trump’s tweets. My final point is that some of the protests are street theater staged by

Republican operatives as part of Trump’s reelection effort. See Talking Points Memo, “Seeing The “Open the Economy” Protests In Their Proper Light.” As Josh Marshall notes, the “turnout is heavily stocked with militia types and the kinds of groups who turned out for the

Charlottesville protests a couple of years ago.” Marshall goes on to say the bigger thing is that for now they appear highly orchestrated. In Michigan, they appear to be in part in reaction to polling showing severe declines in public support for President Trump.

They’re organized by groups funded in large part by the DeVos family. In other words, traditional “dark money” supporters of Trump, such as the DeVos family, are funding Trump political rallies in states where support for Trump is in “severe decline.” I’ll bet dollars to donuts

governors rightly described his remarks "delusional.” The Guardian, “Governors: Trump making ‘delusional’ comments on testing and restrictions.” Predictably, Mike Pence said that Trump was not calling for resistance to social distancing orders. Politico, “Pence defends

Trump's 'LIBERATE' tweets.” When asked why Trump was undermining the governors’ efforts to maintain social distancing, Pence replied, “I don't accept your premise, and I don't think most Americans do either.” Trump quickly made a liar of Pence by saying that observing social

distancing was “politically correct,” not public health policy. Another administration official, Stephen Moore, compared the protestors to Rosa Parks—a hero of the civil rights movement who refused to give up her seat to a white passenger. See Talking Points Memo, “Trump Adviser

Takes Heat For Likening Stay-At-Home Protesters To Rosa Parks.” The protesters who showed up in Michigan to protest Governor Gretchen Witmer’s orders were no Rosa Parks. They showed up with assault rifles, waved Confederate Flags, and held signs with Swastikas that said,

“Heil Witmer!” Trump said that the protestors “seem to be very responsible people to me. See The Guardian, “Trump calls protesters against stay-at-home orders 'very responsible'.” Trump is one riot away from his second “fine people on both sides” Charlottesville moment.

But this time, the “fine people” with assault rifles and Confederate flags are endangering the lives of their parents, grandparents and loved ones. @ScottWapnerCNBC @jimcramer @tomkeene @riskreversal @SquawkCNBC @andrewrsorkin
